An ```onChange``` event handler returns a ```Synthetic Event``` object which contains useful meta data such as the target input’s **id, name, and current value**.

React creates a ```SyntheticEvent``` for each event. It has been passed into event handlers or callback functions and contains details of the event. 
Just like &lt;Toogle /&gt; has event handler props :  ```(checked: boolean, event: SyntheticEvent) =&gt; void``` which means you will get ```boolean``` value when you toggle the ```&lt;Toggle /&gt;``` component.

some of the synthetic events: 
```
    bubbles: boolean
    cancelable: boolean
    currentTarget: DOMEventTarget
    defaultPrevented: boolean
    eventPhase: number
    isTrusted: boolean
    nativeEvent: DOMEvent
    preventDefault(): void
    isDefaultPrevented(): boolean
    stopPropagation(): void
    isPropagationStopped(): boolean
    target: DOMEventTarget
    timeStamp: number
    type: string
```
